------------------------- MODULE RollbackRetryableApplyOps -------------------------
\*
\* A specification of the rollback / retryable-write interaction for atomic
\* applyOps oplog entries. Tracks SERVER-126373: when rollback reverts a primary's
\* oplog suffix, every atomic applyOps entry that carries a retryable-write marker
\* (i.e. its inner ops were generated by a retryable client write whose lsid/txnNumber
\* must be reconstructed into config.transactions) MUST be classified as retryable so
\* the rollback recovery path refreshes the session transaction table. Misclassifying
\* such an entry as plain-CRUD strands the retry record and lets the client's retry
\* re-apply the same statement on the new primary.
\*
\* To run the model-checker:
\*     cd src/mongo/tla_plus
\*     ./model-check.sh Replication/RollbackRetryableApplyOps/RollbackRetryableApplyOps
\*

EXTENDS Integers, FiniteSets, Sequences, TLC

\* The set of oplog entries that may be appended on the primary before rollback fires.
\* Each entry is a record:
\*   [ kind     |-> "crud" | "applyOps",
\*     atomic   |-> BOOLEAN,           \* applyOps only: o.applyOps run atomically
\*     retryable|-> BOOLEAN,           \* carries lsid + txnNumber + stmtIds
\*     lsid     |-> Lsid | NoLsid,
\*     txnNum   |-> Nat ]
\*
CONSTANTS Crud, AtomicApplyOpsRetryable, AtomicApplyOpsPlain, NonAtomicApplyOps

\* The set of logical session ids used by the model.
CONSTANTS Lsids

\* Sentinel value meaning "no lsid present on this oplog entry".
CONSTANT NoLsid

\* Bound on log length and on the number of rollback events to keep state finite.
CONSTANTS MaxLogLen, MaxRollbacks

(*****************************************************************************)
(* Variables                                                                 *)
(*****************************************************************************)

\* The primary's oplog modeled as a sequence of entries.
VARIABLE oplog

\* The set of oplog entries that the rollback path has already classified as
\* retryable (and therefore scheduled for config.transactions refresh).
VARIABLE classifiedRetryable

\* The set of oplog entries the rollback path classified as non-retryable.
VARIABLE classifiedNonRetryable

\* The contents of config.transactions on the rolling-back node after rollback
\* has finished refreshing it. A function from Lsid -> Nat (highest txnNumber).
VARIABLE sessionTable

\* Count of rollback events so we can bound the state space.
VARIABLE rollbackCount

\* Whether we are currently inside a rollback. Used to sequence Classify /
\* RefreshSessions / FinishRollback so the model checker explores them.
VARIABLE rollbackPhase

vars == <<oplog, classifiedRetryable, classifiedNonRetryable,
          sessionTable, rollbackCount, rollbackPhase>>

(*****************************************************************************)
(* Helpers                                                                   *)
(*****************************************************************************)

\* The kinds of entries the model may append.
EntryKinds == {Crud, AtomicApplyOpsRetryable, AtomicApplyOpsPlain, NonAtomicApplyOps}

\* Project an entry into a record with the rollback-classifier-visible fields.
MkEntry(kind, lsid, txnNum) ==
    [ kind      |-> kind,
      atomic    |-> kind \in {AtomicApplyOpsRetryable, AtomicApplyOpsPlain},
      retryable |-> kind \in {Crud, AtomicApplyOpsRetryable} /\ lsid /= NoLsid,
      lsid      |-> lsid,
      txnNum    |-> txnNum ]

\* The classifier under test: does the rollback recovery path think this entry
\* is retryable? An entry is retryable iff it carries an lsid AND either it is a
\* plain CRUD op OR it is an *atomic* applyOps carrying retryable-write markers.
\* (Non-atomic applyOps are unprepared transactions; their retryable handling is
\* covered by the transactions rollback path, not this one.)
IsRetryableForRollback(e) ==
    /\ e.lsid /= NoLsid
    /\ \/ e.kind = Crud
       \/ /\ e.kind = AtomicApplyOpsRetryable
          /\ e.atomic = TRUE

\* The "ground-truth" oracle: an entry truly needs config.transactions refresh
\* iff it was authored by a retryable client write. The model marks that as
\* e.retryable.
TrulyRetryable(e) == e.retryable

(*****************************************************************************)
(* Initial state                                                             *)
(*****************************************************************************)

Init ==
    /\ oplog = << >>
    /\ classifiedRetryable = {}
    /\ classifiedNonRetryable = {}
    /\ sessionTable = [s \in Lsids |-> 0]
    /\ rollbackCount = 0
    /\ rollbackPhase = "steady"

(*****************************************************************************)
(* Actions                                                                   *)
(*****************************************************************************)

\* Append a new oplog entry. We non-deterministically pick the kind, an lsid
\* (or NoLsid), and a txnNumber. Only allowed in steady state.
AppendOplog ==
    /\ rollbackPhase = "steady"
    /\ Len(oplog) < MaxLogLen
    /\ \E kind \in EntryKinds, lsid \in Lsids \cup {NoLsid}, txn \in 1..3 :
         LET e == MkEntry(kind, lsid, txn)
         IN oplog' = Append(oplog, e)
    /\ UNCHANGED <<classifiedRetryable, classifiedNonRetryable,
                    sessionTable, rollbackCount, rollbackPhase>>

\* Enter rollback. Snapshots happen now; no more entries appended until done.
BeginRollback ==
    /\ rollbackPhase = "steady"
    /\ rollbackCount < MaxRollbacks
    /\ Len(oplog) > 0
    /\ rollbackPhase' = "classifying"
    /\ UNCHANGED <<oplog, classifiedRetryable, classifiedNonRetryable,
                    sessionTable, rollbackCount>>

\* For every entry in the rollback suffix, the rollback recovery path applies
\* IsRetryableForRollback and partitions entries into retryable / non-retryable
\* bins. This is the action SERVER-126373 changes: prior to the fix, atomic
\* retryable applyOps fell into classifiedNonRetryable because the classifier
\* only inspected e.kind = Crud.
ClassifyEntries ==
    /\ rollbackPhase = "classifying"
    /\ classifiedRetryable' =
          { i \in 1..Len(oplog) : IsRetryableForRollback(oplog[i]) }
    /\ classifiedNonRetryable' =
          { i \in 1..Len(oplog) : ~IsRetryableForRollback(oplog[i]) }
    /\ rollbackPhase' = "refreshing"
    /\ UNCHANGED <<oplog, sessionTable, rollbackCount>>

\* For every entry in classifiedRetryable, refresh config.transactions with the
\* (lsid, txnNum) on the entry. Modeled as a max-merge: the table records the
\* highest txnNumber seen for each lsid. Entries in classifiedNonRetryable are
\* skipped.
RefreshSessions ==
    /\ rollbackPhase = "refreshing"
    /\ sessionTable' =
          [ s \in Lsids |->
              LET observed ==
                    { oplog[i].txnNum : i \in
                        { j \in classifiedRetryable : oplog[j].lsid = s } }
              IN IF observed = {}
                 THEN sessionTable[s]
                 ELSE LET hi == CHOOSE x \in observed : \A y \in observed : x >= y
                      IN IF hi > sessionTable[s] THEN hi ELSE sessionTable[s] ]
    /\ rollbackPhase' = "finishing"
    /\ UNCHANGED <<oplog, classifiedRetryable, classifiedNonRetryable,
                    rollbackCount>>

\* Finish rollback: drop the rolled-back suffix from the oplog, increment the
\* rollback counter, and return to steady state ready for the next round.
FinishRollback ==
    /\ rollbackPhase = "finishing"
    /\ oplog' = << >>
    /\ rollbackCount' = rollbackCount + 1
    /\ rollbackPhase' = "steady"
    /\ UNCHANGED <<classifiedRetryable, classifiedNonRetryable, sessionTable>>

Next ==
    \/ AppendOplog
    \/ BeginRollback
    \/ ClassifyEntries
    \/ RefreshSessions
    \/ FinishRollback

Spec == Init /\ [][Next]_vars /\ WF_vars(BeginRollback)
        /\ WF_vars(ClassifyEntries)
        /\ WF_vars(RefreshSessions)
        /\ WF_vars(FinishRollback)

(*****************************************************************************)
(* Invariants                                                                *)
(*****************************************************************************)

\* SAFETY 1: every truly retryable entry in the rollback suffix is classified as
\* retryable. This is the SERVER-126373 invariant. If the classifier inspects
\* only e.kind = Crud (the pre-fix behavior), atomic-applyOps-retryable entries
\* with the same lsid/txnNum trigger a counterexample: the entry sits in
\* classifiedNonRetryable while TrulyRetryable holds.
AtomicRetryableApplyOpsIdentified ==
    rollbackPhase \in {"refreshing", "finishing", "steady"}
    => \A i \in 1..Len(oplog) :
         TrulyRetryable(oplog[i]) => i \in classifiedRetryable

\* SAFETY 2: classifiedRetryable and classifiedNonRetryable partition the
\* rollback suffix. No entry can be in both, none missing.
ClassificationPartition ==
    rollbackPhase \in {"refreshing", "finishing", "steady"}
    => /\ classifiedRetryable \cap classifiedNonRetryable = {}
       /\ classifiedRetryable \cup classifiedNonRetryable
            = { i : i \in 1..Len(oplog) }

\* SAFETY 3: after RefreshSessions runs, every lsid that owned a truly
\* retryable entry has its txnNumber reflected in sessionTable. This is the
\* observable end-state guarantee: a client that retries on the new primary
\* will hit the same stmtId in config.transactions and the write will not be
\* duplicated.
SessionTableReflectsRetryableEntries ==
    rollbackPhase \in {"finishing", "steady"}
    => \A i \in 1..Len(oplog) :
         TrulyRetryable(oplog[i]) =>
            sessionTable[oplog[i].lsid] >= oplog[i].txnNum

\* SAFETY 4: rollback never loses a retryable record by leaving its lsid at
\* zero when the rollback suffix contained an authored retryable write for it.
NoSilentRetryableLoss ==
    rollbackPhase = "steady"
    => \A s \in Lsids :
         (\E i \in 1..Len(oplog) : oplog[i].lsid = s /\ TrulyRetryable(oplog[i]))
            => sessionTable[s] > 0

=============================================================================
